The handshake is an HTTP Upgrade. The client sends a `GET` with `Upgrade: websocket`, `Connection: Upgrade`, and a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`. The server proves it understood the protocol by concatenating that key with the magic GUID `258EAFA5-E914-47DA-95CA-C5AB0DC85B11`, SHA-1 hashing, and base64-encoding the result into `Sec-WebSocket-Accept`. Verified in Node against the RFC 6455 example:

```js
import crypto from "node:crypto";
const key = "dGhlIHNhbXBsZSBub25jZQ=="; // sent by the client
const GUID = "258EAFA5-E914-47DA-95CA-C5AB0DC85B11";
const accept = crypto.createHash("sha1").update(key + GUID).digest("base64");
console.log(accept); // s3pPLMBiTxaQ9kYGzzhZRbK+xOo=
```

After the upgrade, communication is framed (text opcode `0x1`, binary `0x2`), not raw HTTP. WebSockets are deliberately *not* governed by the CORS preflight model — there is no `OPTIONS` preflight; instead the server is expected to inspect the `Origin` header itself and reject unwanted origins.

This is one of the most practical differences between the two. `EventSource` has reconnection in the spec: when the connection drops it waits a short, implementation-defined delay (a few seconds; the server can tune it with a `retry:` field) and reconnects, sending `Last-Event-ID` so the server can resume.

The native `WebSocket` does none of this — a drop fires `onclose` and the socket stays closed. You implement reconnection yourself, ideally with **exponential backoff plus jitter** so a server restart does not trigger a synchronized stampede from every client at once:

```js
let delay = 1000;
function connect() {
  const ws = new WebSocket("wss://example.com/chat");
  ws.onopen = () => { delay = 1000; };          // reset after a success
  ws.onclose = () => {
    const wait = delay + Math.random() * 1000;  // jitter avoids a thundering herd
    setTimeout(connect, wait);
    delay = Math.min(delay * 2, 30000);         // capped exponential backoff
  };
}
connect();
```
